  "data": {
    "query": "SPP asset registration resource types integrated market protocols",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "SPP",
      "data_type": "report",
      "year_start": 2020,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": "gte"
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "abaade85-205c-4288-b084-bdd82c69aa46",
        "score": 0.56601596,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report discusses two main topics related to power market transactions and market-to-market processes.\n\n1. **Fixed and Dispatchable Transactions:**\n   - The average monthly dispatchable transactions increased from 80 MW in 2020 to 100 MW in 2021.\n   - The highest dispatchable transactions occurred in November, peaking at nearly 200 MW.\n   - Up-to-TUC transactions were limited to February and March, averaging 24 MW each month.\n   - Fixed transactions dominate interchange transactions due to factors such as bilateral contracts with external entities, Southwestern Power Administration hydro contracts, and generally lower prices in the SPP market compared to other RTOs.\n   - To improve market efficiency, participants are encouraged to use dispatchable and up-to-TUC imports and exports more, as these allow setting a specific strike price, enabling more economic imports and exports.\n\n2. **Market-to-Market (M2M) Process:**\n   - SPP started the M2M process with MISO in March 2015, fulfilling a FERC requirement that also included regulation compensation and long-term congestion rights.\n   - Each Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) is allocated property rights on market-to-market constraints, called firm flow entitlements (FFE).\n   - Each RTO calculates its real-time usage (market flow) and exchanges money (market-to-market settlements) for redispatch based on the difference between market flow and firm flow entitlement.\n   - The non-monitoring RTO receives money from the monitoring RTO if its market flow is below its firm flow entitlement and pays if above.\n   - Figure 2-44 (not shown) illustrates monthly payments between SPP and MISO, where positive values indicate payments from MISO to SPP, and negative values indicate payments from SPP to MISO.\n\nFootnotes clarify that the M2M process and related mechanisms were implemented one year after the SPP Integrated Marketplace go-live, allowing efficient management of constraints by exchanging information and using the more economic redispatch. The monitoring RTO typically manages the limiting constraint and has the most impact and resources for relieving congestion.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_82.jpg",
          "page_num": 82,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0652ae7b-d68c-436c-ac73-ce0e93668550",
        "score": 0.5624876,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report focuses on the Integrated Marketplace operated by SPP, a Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC). SPP was granted RTO status in 2004 and provides various services to its members, including reliability coordination, tariff administration, regional scheduling, reserve sharing, transmission expansion planning, wholesale electricity market operations, and training. The report specifically addresses the 2023 calendar year of the SPP wholesale electricity market, known as the Integrated Marketplace, which began on March 1, 2014.\n\nThe Integrated Marketplace features a full day-ahead market with transmission congestion rights, virtual trading, a reliability unit commitment process, a real-time balancing market, and a price-based operating reserves market. A key benefit of the day-ahead market is improved efficiency in daily resource commitments, along with joint optimization of available capacity for energy and operating reserves. SPP also implemented a single balancing authority as part of this marketplace.\n\nThe SPP market footprint is located in the westernmost part of the Eastern Interconnection, bordered by Midcontinent ISO (MISO) to the east, Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) to the south, and the Western Interconnection to the west. The document references a figure showing the operating regions of nine RTO/ISO markets in the U.S. and Canada, along with a detailed view of the SPP footprint. Additionally, the SPP market connects with non-RTO/ISO areas such as Saskatchewan Power Corporation, Associated Electric Cooperative, and Southwestern Power Administration. The footnote clarifies that Southwestern Power Administration is part of the SPP RTO, Reliability Coordinator, and Reserve Sharing Group footprints, while Associated Electric Cooperative belongs to the SPP Reserve Sharing Group.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2023/page_36.jpg",
          "page_num": 36,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET 2023",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "241cfaaf-910a-4d5a-a3fc-19ec05405108",
        "score": 0.55117273,
        "text": "This document page from Southwest Power Pool, Inc.'s Market Monitoring Unit discusses the unit commitment and dispatch process within the Integrated Marketplace, focusing on the commitment process.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- SPP implemented a ramp capability product on March 1, 2022.\n- There has been a shift in the average percent of total offered capacity by commitment status, with a 5 percentage point decrease in self-commit status and a 5 percentage point increase in market status.\n\nSection 3.1 Commitment Process explains that the Integrated Marketplace uses centralized unit commitment to efficiently schedule and dispatch generation resources to meet energy demand and operating reserve requirements. Most commitments start in the day-ahead market, which aims to commit enough capacity to meet the loads bid into that market. However, due to differences between day-ahead and real-time conditions and locational issues, additional capacity often needs to be committed outside the day-ahead market.\n\nThis additional commitment is managed through reliability unit commitment (RUC) processes and manual commitments. SPP employs five reliability commitment processes:\n\n1. Multi-day reliability assessment (MDRA)\n2. Day-ahead reliability unit commitment (DA RUC) process\n3. Intra-day reliability unit commitment (ID RUC) process\n4. Short-term intra-day reliability unit commitment (ST RUC) process\n5. Manual commitment instructions issued by the Regional Transmission Organization (RTO)\n\nThe page also includes a timeline figure (Figure 3-1) illustrating when these various commitment processes occur relative to the operating day, showing the sequence from multi-day reliability assessment through day-ahead market and RUC processes to intra-day and manual commitments.\n\nA footnote references the tariff revisions related to the ramp capability product (FERC Docket No. ER20-1617).",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_104.jpg",
          "page_num": 104,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2d9bb31e-8d28-4809-ae92-ac2747cd8153",
        "score": 0.53704274,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report provides an overview of key market statistics and introduces the Integrated Marketplace.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- Net market-to-market payments from MISO to SPP in 2021 were $87 million, similar to 2020's $83 million. Excluding February, payments would have been $139 million, a 68% increase from 2020. November had the highest payments at nearly $30 million.\n- Cleared virtual energy bids and offers as a percentage of load increased to 25% in 2021 from 19% in 2020.\n- Average profit per cleared virtual megawatt after fees rose sharply from $0.63/MW in 2020 to $8.26/MW in 2021. Excluding February, the average profit was $1.84, more than double the 2020 figure.\n\nThe section titled \"The Integrated Marketplace\" explains that SPP is a Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) authorized by FERC to ensure reliable power supply, adequate transmission infrastructure, and competitive wholesale electricity prices. SPP was granted RTO status in 2004 and offers services such as reliability coordination, tariff administration, regional scheduling, reserve sharing, transmission expansion planning, wholesale market operations, and training.\n\nThe Integrated Marketplace, launched on March 1, 2014, includes a full day-ahead market with transmission congestion rights, virtual trading, a reliability unit commitment process, a real-time balancing market, and a price-based operating reserves market. It also features a single balancing authority. The primary benefit of the day-ahead market is improved efficiency in daily resource commitments, along with joint optimization of available capacity for energy and operating reserves.\n\nThe page is from the \"State of the Market 2021\" report, page 26.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_40.jpg",
          "page_num": 40,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "962b5e7a-52d1-4aa2-accd-68840d0ee489",
        "score": 0.53641737,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) provides recommendations focused on two main areas:\n\n1. **Enhancing Commitment of Resources to Increase Ramping Flexibility (2017.2):**\n   - In 2017, the MMU recommended that SPP and its stakeholders address inadequate ramping flexibility by modifying market rules to improve resource commitment and ramping flexibility.\n   - Initially, the focus was on enhancing the decommitment of resources, but by 2018, the recommendation was updated to also include improving how resources are committed.\n   - The MMU suggested exploring various options to address commitment concerns and increase flexibility.\n   - This initiative is included in the SPP Roadmap and is considered a high priority.\n\n2. **Enhancing Market Rules for Energy Storage Resources (2017.3):**\n   - SPP implemented energy storage design changes in 2021 to comply with FERC Order No. 841.\n   - The MMU supported the implementation but identified additional enhancements needed for better integration of electric storage resources in the SPP markets.\n   - Multiple initiatives were added to the SPP Roadmap to address these enhancements.\n   - The MMU had previously recommended including mitigation measures for excessively low offers, but this was not reflected in the current initiatives.\n   - The MMU plans to work with SPP to add an initiative to the Roadmap that incorporates this recommendation.\n\nOverall, the page highlights ongoing efforts and recommendations by the MMU to improve market rules and resource flexibility, particularly focusing on ramping capabilities and energy storage integration within the SPP market framework.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_288.jpg",
          "page_num": 288,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

